properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heat event begins Friday. Daytime temperatures are expected to reach the low 30's with humidex values in the mid to high 30's on Friday and Saturday. Overnight temperatures will remain near twenty, providing little relief from the heat. Temperatures will cool off slightly on Sunday. Hot and humid air can also bring deteriorating air quality and can result in the Air Quality Health Index approaching the high risk category. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Watch for the effects of heat illness: swelling, rash, cramps, fainting, heat exhaustion, heat stroke and the worsening of some health conditions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 5:36 p.m. CDT, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a line of severe thunderstorms capable of producing very strong wind gusts, nickel to ping pong ball size hail and heavy rain. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Intense lightning is likely with any thunderstorm that develops. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heat wave in sight. A warm and humid air mass will gradually settle over Southern Quebec. Maximum temperatures are forecast to hover around 30 degrees on Saturday, Sunday and Monday. The weather will be particularly moist Sunday and Monday when humidex values will hover between 38 and 40. It will be hot at night as well. A cold front will bring some respite Tuesday or Wednesday next week. Reschedule or plan your outdoor activities during the coolest time of the day. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
